      "output": "At its simplest, **water** is a clear, odorless, and tasteless liquid that is essential for all known forms of life. \n\nTo understand water fully, it helps to look at it through a few different lenses:\n\n### 1. The Chemical View\nScientifically, water is a chemical compound. Its chemical formula is **$H_2O$**. This means that every single molecule of water is made up of:\n*   Two atoms of **Hydrogen** ($H$)\n*   One atom of **Oxygen** ($O$)\n\nThese atoms are bound together tightly, creating a molecule that has a slight positive charge on the hydrogen side and a slight negative charge on the oxygen side. This \"polarity\" is what makes water such a great solvent—it is able to dissolve salt, sugar, nutrients, and minerals easily.\n\n### 2. The States of Matter\nWater is famous for being the only natural substance on Earth that exists abundantly in three distinct states:\n*   **Liquid:** What we normally drink and find in rivers, lakes, and oceans.\n*   **Solid (Ice):** Formed when water freezes at or below 0°C (32°F). Interestingly, solid water (ice) is less dense than liquid water, which is why ice floats.\n*   **Gas (Vapor/Steam):** Formed when water boils at 100°C (212°F) or evaporates into the air.\n\n### 3. Its Importance to Earth\nWater shapes our planet more than any other substance:\n*   **Coverage:** About **71% of the Earth's surface** is covered in water, mostly in the oceans (which hold about 96.5% of all Earth's water).\n*   **The Water Cycle:** Water is constantly recycled through evaporation, condensation (clouds), and precipitation (rain and snow) in a closed system. The water you drink today is the same water that dinosaurs drank millions of years ago.\n\n### 4. Its Importance to Life\nWater is the cradle of life. \n*   **Biology:** The human body is made up of about 60% water. It regulates our temperature, lubricates joints, flushes out waste, and carries nutrients through our blood.\n*   **Habitation:** Without water, plants cannot photosynthesize, animals cannot survive, and ecosystems would collapse. \n\nIn short, water is the"
